<p class="eyebrow">Open Source</p>
<h1>Open Source</h1>
<p class="lede">Tools, libraries, and reference implementations VoiceTel publishes under open licenses. We use these in production and ship them so customers and the broader telecom community can build on the same foundations we do.</p>

<h2>What we publish</h2>
<p>Phase 1 placeholder. The full list of repositories, license summaries, and contribution guidelines lands per the brief's <code>§7</code> spec for company pages. Expected sections:</p>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Voice markup reference</strong> — sample VoiceML applications and migration tooling.</li>
	<li><strong>SDN appliance image</strong> — reference build for the VoiceTel SDN Pi image.</li>
	<li><strong>SDK clients</strong> — REST API clients and SIP/voice helper libraries.</li>
	<li><strong>Integration guides</strong> — example configs for Asterisk, FreePBX, FreeSWITCH, FusionPBX, Kamailio, OpenSIPS.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Licensing</h2>
<p>All VoiceTel-published open source code ships under permissive licenses (MIT or Apache-2.0 unless otherwise noted at the repository level). Documentation and reference content are typically CC BY 4.0.</p>

